gomodel:SYNGO_2140  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Background: Myosin IIb is a known actin based motor that consists of multiple subunits. The Myh10 gene encodes the heavy chain of this complex.\n\nFig.1: \"Myosin IIb is required for stable LTP and activity-related spine actin polymerization\"\nKD of MYH10 in the hippocampus CA1 area does not affect basal neuronal communication but impairs stability of LTP induction. \"Slices expressing MyH10-shRNAs demonstrated significantly depressed levels of activity-induced spine F-actin structures\"\n\nThe rest of the experiments detail this the role of Myosin IIb, but are not specific at the Myh10 gene level. Fig.3: NMDA receptor stimulation and LTP induction triggers one or more second messenger systems (tested with ROCK inhibition) that activate the myosin II motor.\n\nTogether: \"In vivo delivery of shRNAs that targeted MyH10, the heavy chain of Myosin IIb, prevented F-actin polymerization and stable LTP.\". Experimental description: \"Unless otherwise stated, acute hippocampal slices (350 μm) were cut transverse to the long axis of the hippocampus from adult (4-6 weeks) male Sprague Dawley rats and maintained ...\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6153-3586" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2666-0758" ;
        dc:date           "2017-12-17" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2140" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

